    "import dpm_tools as dpm\n",
    "import porespy as ps\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "16f11c22",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Demonstration image\n",
    "\n",
    "To demonstrate the maximum inscribed spheres, we generate a simple 3D binary image using the [PoreSpy blobs generator](https://porespy.org/examples/generators/tutorials/making_blobs.html) function. The example image size is $100 \\times 100 \\times 100$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "f38ca6e9",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "(-0.5, 99.5, 99.5, -0.5)"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 2,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 600x600 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "image = ps.generators.blobs(shape=[100, 100, 100])\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=[6, 6])\n",
    "im = ax.imshow(image[50], cmap=\"binary_r\")\n",
    "fig.colorbar(im, fraction=0.046, pad=0.04)\n",
    "ax.axis(False)"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "## Maximum Inscribed Spheres\n",
    "\n",
    "Maximum inscribed spheres are the largest spheres that can fit entirely within a given shape or region, touching its boundary without crossing it. In image processing and porous media analysis, they are used to quantify local pore size, geometric accessibility, or distance to constrictions.\n",
    "\n",
    "The ``mis`` function in the ``dpm_tools.metrics`` module expects a 2D or 3D ``np.ndarray`` where the phase of interest (foreground) is labeled as 1. The function accepts keyword arguments as [``porespy.filters.local_thickness()``](https://porespy.org/modules/generated/generated/porespy.filters.local_thickness.html)."
   ]
  },
